tasks.content: Hover your mouse cursor over the Experience Builder application's header, then select "Edit Header" (1). Next, change the "Title" (2) by clicking on the text "The 3 Valleys". You can do this either by double-clicking the text or clicking it once and then selecting the pencil icon (3).

If you want to change the font or size, the easiest way is to select all the text you want to edit. You can do this using your mouse or by pressing the keyboard shortcut Ctrl+A, which will select the entire text. This will display the text editing panel (4).
Download the file "Mountain-Logo.png", then click on the image icon (5). Choose the "Select an image" option (6), and in the next step, upload the downloaded image by clicking "Upload" (7).
In the next step, click on the word "Subtitle" (8) and either delete it using the "Delete" key or by clicking the trash bin icon (9).

You will see a prompt asking if you're sure you want to delete the widget from all devices and states. This means that this specific text widget will also be removed from the mobile and tablet views. However, don’t worry about that at this stage—we are currently focusing only on the desktop version of the application. There is a dedicated video in the additional section that explains how to handle mobile views in detail: Lecture: Disconnecting Views - Application Responsiveness - Full Screen - Tablet.

Now, for the first time, we will add a widget from the "Insert" panel. To do this, click the plus icon in the left panel (11), then search for the "Map" widget (12). Drag it onto the canvas/workspace of your application and drop it (13).
Click on the added Map widget (14), then select the first option, "Align" (15), and choose the last option (16), "Full Size".

After adding the widget, a contextual menu will appear on the right side of the screen for the selected widget-in our case, the Map widget. Now add the map "XBLD_WebMap" that we created earlier. Click "Select Map" (17), then choose "Add new data" (18).

In this way, we've learned how to add a WebMap to an Experience Builder (EB) application. While it is possible to add individual layers (services) directly to the application, in most cases we want widgets to work with the map. Therefore, in about 90% of cases, I built applications based on layers that are already part of the WebMap.
Later in the course, you will learn what consequences arise when your layers are added separately rather than being part of the map.
In the last step, we need to specify which map will power our widget (21).

The map that has been added to our widget is visible (22). The Map widget also allows the use of two maps-or even a web scene-which we will explore later. For now, just note that this option exists (23).
Close the WebMap source selection panel by clicking the "X" icon (24).
